  "answer": "**Old English 'goldwīne' (gold-friend/lord)** appears as a kenning—a compact poetic compound—for a generous lord who binds retainers through gifts of gold (treasure, rings), evoking the warmth of reciprocal loyalty in the heroic comitatus (lord-thane bond). A representative line comes from *The Wanderer*, where the exiled speaker laments his lost protector:\n\n> ...siþþan geara iū **goldwine** minne  \n> hrūsan heolstre biwrah...\n\nRendered in translation: \"...since in years gone by **my gold-lord** / my dear gold-friend hid [me] in the earth's shelter...\"[^1]\n\nThe \"warmth\" here stems explicitly from **gift relations**: gold as the tangible symbol of the lord's favor, fostering bonds of service and protection amid life's mutability.[^2]\n\n**Urdu 'mehr' (sun / kindness, affection, mercy)** is polysemous, layering solar warmth (physical light/heat) with emotional generosity (solar as metaphor for benevolent bonds). A fine example is the opening ghazal (ode) title and radīf (rhyme-word) from Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib*, playing on both senses across couplets:\n\n> **Az mehr** ta-ba-zarra dīl-o-dīl hai ā'īna  \n> Har shab chirāġh-e dil jalā'e na shab-parast\n\nTranslated: \"From **the sun** [or mercy] to a mote of dust, heart-to-heart is a mirror— / Why does not the night-worshipper light the lamp of the heart every night?\"[^3]\n\nHere, 'mehr' evokes radiant warmth as both literal sunlight (optical mirror-play) and metaphorical kindness (hearts reflecting love/mercy), without direct reference to material exchange.\n\nDoes the \"warmth\" in each arise from the same source—**gift relations** (as in OE lordship reciprocity)—or something else (e.g., natural/cosmic radiance in Urdu, extending to divine/human benevolence)?",
